As governors of provinces there was no distinction 74 between the proconsuls and propraetore, but the more lucrative provinces were usually assigned to the former. In his province the governor was supreme, at once commender of the army, chief executive‚ and judge in both civil and criminal cases. In such a position there was abundant opportunity for gaining immense wealth. In times of peace ⁷⁵ there were a thousand methods of extortion, and the average governor left none untried; in time of war there were citios ’ to be plundered and captives to be sold as slaves. A pro· vincial governorship was looked upon by Roman nobles as a gold mine from which to pay their debts and buy new pleasures and honors.
